Recap of Prediction Problem

The objective of this project was to look into movie revenue and whether the revenue of a movie could be predicted, somewhat accurately, by the other features of the movie.

Final Model Analysis

TableÂ 3 provides the final metric values on the Yeo-Johnson scale, with the final MAE value of 73.3. Supplemental metrics were calculated, RMSE and R-squared, and their values are 99.2 and 0.671, respectively.


Being on the Yeo-Johnson scale, it is difficult to really interpret the MAE and RMSE, so below is the table of the metrics on the original scale ($).

The RMSE of 99.2 in dollars is almost $170 million and the MAE of 73.4 is equivalent to $100.4 million. The R-squared also reduces slightly because of the scaling changes, which is not a very good sign as it was already at 0.667. From TableÂ 3, the R-squared of 0.671 means about 67.1% of the variance in the data can be explained by the model, which is not necessarily up to par with the standards of a âgoodâ predictive model. This leaves a lot of the reasoning of the changes up in the air, since there could be a plethora of reasons for the variance that is not captured by the model. The definition of a good model can vary depending on problem type, so overall, 67.1% is not the best and it is not the worst.

Furthermore, FigureÂ 1 is a plot of the predicted revenue by the actual revenue on the Yeo-Johnson scale. There are 2 main clusters of points from 100 to 500 and 625 to 750. The proportion of predictions above the actual values and below the actual values are fairly equal, at least in those clusters.

Zoomed in, we see the distribution of the previous FigureÂ 2 but restricted to between 0 and 500,000,000. This plot shows that there is a bit more overfitting then underfitting present, which can be from the Boosted Tree model, since tree models are more prone to overfitting.

Conclusion

In this process, we found that my modeling does not serve too well for my prediction problem, which could be from my own doing in feature engineering or it could be that the dataset and type of problem overall is not the best for predictive modeling. For the future, it would be helpful to have a more comprehensive dataset and/or to explore more complex and insightful methods in the feature engineering phase. The different selection of models and tuning parameters could also aid in a better outcome if the prediction problem as a whole can be captured through this scope of modeling.
